Joseph,<br>
     A military organization exists for the &quot;controlled&quot; application of violence in the pursuit of military objectives.  Uncontrolled mayhem, while favored by Viking berzerkers, is not preferred.  There are people like Calley who crack under the stress.  With US troops up to 490,000 at one point, there was bound to be someone somewhere who lost it due to the strain of combat.  While maybe civilian standards didn't always apply; that doesn't mean there were none.  Atrocities were contrary to standing orders.  Besides the immorality of such actions, they are stupid in that they drive the population into the arms of the enemy.                                                           As for other offenses, Long Binh Jail was full of those who seriously violated military standards of conduct.  I spent 10 months pulling court martial duty regularly.  The caseload was primarily Absent Without Leave (AWOL) at 40% and possesion of a drug at 45%.
